<font color="#FF0000">WHY? AN ANSWER</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 16 16:24:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Class Lass,<br><br>
I was a member of the 37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron, stationed in Danang from October 1970 to June 1971.  As stated in the other thread, I knew one of the crew members of the Jolly 375 crew, and in fact flew on that chopper on training and other missions.  I think that I can answer your question in a way that will surprise you, and maybe throw some water on the fires of your rage.<br><br>
Col. Hambleton did not receive special treatment!  This was the normal response to ANY downed flier in the theater, which included in-country, North Vietnam, Laos (where we encountered tanks!) and Cambodia.  Most rescue attempts in-country were handled by the Army, as they had more choppers in more areas than we did.  However, whenever there were aircraft at risk over the North, or over Laos, we were in orbit waiting for a possible rescue attempt.<br><br>
If you can, see &quot;Rescue behind enemy lines,&quot; Sept. 1968 National Geographic Magazine.<br><br>
Between the time I left and the time of the mission to rescue Lt. Col. Hambleton, there was a development which would change rescue tactics in SEA--the introduction by the other side of hand-held heat-seeking ground-to-air missiles. Our normal tactics were to fly very low (at tree top level) and very fast to get into the area.  The assumption was that the small-arms fire was our biggest threat, and that low and fast would not give the enemy time to aim their rifles.  The SAM 2 missiles were usually in fixed sites, and were not dangerous until we were at a much higher altitude.  <br><br>
The introduction of the hand-held heat seekers changed that because these missiles could be fired straight up through a small hole in the jungle canopy, where they would see the heat signature of the aircraft and track it.  I saw a photograph in the mid-1970's of one of these types of missiles going straight up, making a very tight loop, and then tracking the aircraft.  A SAM 2 couldn't do this, and would tumble if it tried.  <br><br>
Unfortunately, we did not know of the existence of these missiles in-country until Lt. Col. Hambleton's mission.  My understanding is that this development is what led to the high loss of aircraft during this mission.<br><br>
What you need to understand is that we went after every possible survivor until either they were rescued, captured, or confirmed dead. Sometimes we went in anyway--we lost Charley King on a trap set with a dead pilot.  The air war went on held until these people were rescued or lost.  <br><br>
Last Memorial Day I posted the Pararescue losses on this site (see Memorial Day, above).  It was this dedication to the rescue effort that led to over 600 saves by the 37th ARRS, and a Presidential Unit Citation.  We all figured that each person out there was worth our best efforts.  We also rescued Korean and other units in trouble.<br><br>
Our motto in Pararescue is &quot;These things we do, THAT OTHERS MAY LIVE.&quot; I don't expect you to completely understand that mind set, but Al Avery, Bill Pearson and the rest of that crew lived for that mission.  They also paid the ultimate price, that others may live.  <br><br>
I do appreciate the question--it's one which hasn't been asked enough.  <br><br>
In the &quot;Pararescue--50 Years&quot; book, the following entry sums up our efforts:<br><br>
Speaking of the end of the Southeast Asia commitment with the Mayaguez incident, the book states, &quot;Thus ended an era of unparalleled valor in which the Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Service and Pararescue, in particular, became the greatest combat aircrew recovery force in the history of aerial warfare.  During the eleven years of conflict, 1964 through 1975, Air Rescue Service personnel were credited with saving 4,120 lives; of these, 2,780 were combat saves.  Rescue was one of the most heavily decorated units in the Department of Defense.&quot;<br><br>
Pararescueman Udo C. J. Fischer in 1972 wrote the following:<br><br>
&quot;NO MORE!<br><br>
&quot;I was with Rescue when the bombs were falling,<br>
And thought, 'No more! This is appalling!'<br>
It was the War of Worlds to end all wars;<br>
So we hoped and prayed up to the stars.<br><br>
&quot;The smoke and pain had not yet cleared,<br>
When things went wild and the world got scared.<br>
Again I was in Rescue, not in the mud, but in the air.<br>
Such hellish mess, and reason to despair.<br><br>
&quot;'War is War!' so someone said,<br>
'No good--just bad and sad.'<br>
WHO ARE THOSE WEENIES WHO START IT ALL;<br>
WHO ARE NOT THERE TO SEE THE GOOD MEN FALL&quot;<br><br>
&quot;This second time around, for bewildered me,<br>
I said, 'No more of this I want to see!'<br>
We saved and helped to ease the pain;<br>
For us in Rescue, the efforts were not in vain.<br><br>
&quot;Some years went by--but not too far--<br>
When things again began to pop: ANOTHER WAR!<br>
Here too, I flew and served to rescue men<br>
To keep them out of the dreadful prison 'pen.'<br><br>
&quot;'MY GOD--THIS IS NO WAY TO LIVE--<br>
TO HAVE THESE WARS AND NO LOVE TO GIVE!'<br>
The suffering--so deep in fright--<br>
Was felt by those who had to serve and fight.<br><br>
&quot;'NO MORE!' I said again--and cried.<br>
The stars above showed Peace in might--<br>
For people on earth, peace was not yet in sight;<br>
We just had hell with no delight.<br><br>
&quot;These rescue folks in war and peace,<br>
Were there to help and bring some ease.<br>
But such is little in so many bloody wars.<br>
What we need--is wisdom from the stars!&quot;<br><br>
Udo C.J. Fischer, 1972<br><br>

